 cause of anovulation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Congenital adrenal hyperplasia","Hyperprolactinaemia","Polycystic ovary syndrome","Premature ovarian insufficiency","Thyroid disease"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPolycystic ovary syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E (PCOS) is the most common endocrine disorder affecting women of reproductive age and the most frequent cause of anovulation. It affects 5-10% of women and is characterised by hyperandrogenism, oligo/anovulation, and polycystic ovarian morphology.\u003C/p\u003E        \u003Cp\u003EWhile \u003Cstrong\u003Econgenital adrenal hyperplasia\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003Ethyroid disease\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003Epremature ovarian insufficiency\u003C/strong\u003E, and \u003Cstrong\u003Ehyperprolactinaemia\u003C/strong\u003E can all cause anovulation, they are less common causes compared to PCOS. These conditions disrupt the hypothalamic-pituitary-ovarian axis through various mechanisms, leading to irregular or absent ovulation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Common causes of anovulation include polycystic ovary syndrome, hypothalamic dysfunction, hyperprolactinaemia, and primary ovarian insufficiency.","Anovulation presents clinically as oligomenorrhoea or amenorrhoea and is a common cause of infertility."],"references":["Melmed, S., Polonsky, K. S., Larsen, P. R., \u0026 Kronenberg, H. M. (2015). Williams textbook of endocrinology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Clark, O. H., Duh, Q. Y., Kebebew, E., Gosnell, J. E., \u0026 Shen, W. T. (Eds.). (2016). Textbook of endocrine surgery. JP Medical Ltd","Young, W. F. (2011). Netter\u0027s Endocrine System: Netter Collection of Medical Illustrations: Endocrine System E-book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Wass, J. A., \u0026 Stewart, P. M. (Eds.). (2011). Oxford textbook of endocrinology and diabetes. Oxford University Press, USA","Arulkumar